WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.400
6.0 English From BBCLearningEnglish.com

2
00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:11.800
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

3
00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:14.200
I'm Pippa and I'm Beth.

4
00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:18.400
Foraging is the activity of walking in the countryside

5
00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:22.400
looking for plants you can eat that grow in the wild.

6
00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.800
That's anything from Blackberries and Chessnets

7
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:28.400
to mushrooms and wild garlic.

8
00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:31.600
It's something humans have always done.

9
00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:35.800
And recently, it's become fashionable among groups of young people.

10
00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:38.200
Pippa have you ever been foraging?

11
00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:42.200
Yes, we used to go and pick Blackberries when I was younger,

12
00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:45.400
but I haven't really done it as an adult.

13
00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:48.400
And I would be a bit nervous to look for mushrooms

14
00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:49.400
or things like that.

15
00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:50.400
What about you?

16
00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:52.000
I'm exactly the same.

17
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.200
If I see a Blackberry on a bush, I will eat it.

18
00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:58.000
But mushrooms, no, too scary.

19
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.800
So in this episode, we'll meet two young women

20
00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:03.200
from different countries who are passionate

21
00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:05.400
about foraging wild food.

22
00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:06.800
They're both self-taught,

23
00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.400
having land to flourish by studying the natural world around them.

24
00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:14.200
And it's important to say that they only eat what they can identify

25
00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:17.600
with 100% certainty, sticking to the rule,

26
00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:20.000
if in doubt, leave it out.

27
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.800
We'll also be learning some useful new words and phrases

28
00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:26.000
all of which you'll find on our website,

29
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.600
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

30
00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:32.200
But before that, I have a question for you, Pippa.

31
00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:36.200
As mentioned, when foraging, you must know for certain

32
00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:37.800
what is safe to eat.

33
00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:42.800
Something definitely not safe to eat is the mushroom death cap.

34
00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:47.600
As the name suggests, it's one of the world's deadliest mushrooms.

35
00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:50.400
And it's common across the British Isles.

36
00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:52.400
But what color is it?

37
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:59.400
Are death cap mushrooms a, brown, b, white, or c, red?

38
00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:04.000
I'm going to say if it's dangerous, maybe it's red.

39
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.200
OK, well, we'll find out later in the program.

40
00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:11.200
First, let's meet Roshana Gray, a wild food foraging,

41
00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:14.000
living in Cape Point, South Africa.

42
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.200
Roshana learned how to forage from her mother-in-law.

43
00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:21.600
As she explains here, to BBC World Service Program, the conversation.

44
00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:23.600
So she is a horticulturalist.

45
00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:26.200
She has a deep knowledge of plants.

46
00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:31.600
And so I would be scanning the landscape and learning about these new plants,

47
00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:35.200
or new to me, and wondering if you could eat them.

48
00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:38.600
Something that's incredibly important and faraging is to know,

49
00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:41.000
110% if you can eat it.

50
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:42.800
Positive identification of the plant.

51
00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:44.800
And so she was my plant person.

52
00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:47.600
Roshana's mother-in-law is a horticulturalist.

53
00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:51.400
A person who studies or grows plants, such as flowers, fruits,

54
00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:52.600
and vegetables.

55
00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:56.800
She has a deep knowledge of the wild plants growing in nature.

56
00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:02.400
A deep knowledge means a thorough understanding of a subject gained from experience and study,

57
00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:04.800
not just knowing the basic facts.

58
00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.600
One skill forages need is scanning the landscape.

59
00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:14.000
Scanning means searching a wide area with your eyes to find some particular thing.

60
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.800
In this case, edible plants and herbs.

61
00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:21.200
And of course, Roshana only eats plants that she can positively identify,

62
00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:25.000
plants that she knows 110% are safe to eat.

63
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Here, the idiom 110% means Roshana is completely sure she has no doubt.

64
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:37.600
And that's important as the consequences of eating poisonous plants are serious, sickness or even death.

65
00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:46.800
Our second female forage, Emily Smith, moved to rural Japan to work on a project cataloging and collecting wild mushrooms.

66
00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:56.400
With around 5000 varieties, 300 of which are edible, mushrooms are an important part of traditional Japanese cooking.

67
00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:06.200
But with names like death cap and a reputation for being poisonous, mushrooms are what many wild forages worry about the most.

68
00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:11.600
Emily discuss these worries with BBC World Service Program, the conversation.

69
00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:18.600
That stigma is a bit misplaced, I think, because plants can be just as dangerous if not more dangerous than mushrooms.

70
00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:21.800
And I think mushrooms have been much maligned.

71
00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:27.000
I mean, you've got to exercise caution as Roshana said, in anything that you pick,

72
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
you need to know what it is before you consume it.

73
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.800
If and out through it out is a very good phrase to say,

74
00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:36.000
Emily thinks there's a stigma around mushrooms.

75
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.600
A stigma is a negative belief about something which is not necessarily true or fair.

76
00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:45.200
In fact, many plants are just as poisonous as mushrooms.

77
00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:52.600
The main thing is to exercise caution, to act with care and attention so as to avoid possible dangers.

78
00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:54.800
In other words, to be careful.

79
00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:59.800
And the best way of doing that is learning the difference between what safety and what's not.

80
00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.800
Speaking of which, what was the answer to your question, Beth?

81
00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:07.000
Ah, I asked you, what color are death-capped mushrooms?

82
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:12.200
You said red, which I also thought was the answer, but actually, they are white.

83
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:19.200
Right, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learned about foraging, starting with horticulturalist,

84
00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:22.200
a person who studies or grows plants.

85
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:29.200
If you have a deep knowledge of a subject, you have a thorough understanding of it gained from experience and study.

86
00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:35.000
Scanning involves searching a wide area with your eyes to find some particular thing.

87
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:41.200
If you're 110% sure about something, you're absolutely certain you have no doubt.

88
00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:45.200
A stigma is an unfair negative belief about something.

89
00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:50.200
And finally, to exercise caution is a more formal way of saying to be careful.

90
00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:54.400
Something you should definitely remember if you go wild foraging yourself.

91
00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.600
Once again, our six minutes are up.

92
00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:02.200
If you enjoyed this episode, you'll find a quiz and worksheet to practice the vocabulary on our website.

93
00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:04.600
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

94
00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:06.600
See you again soon. Bye for now.

95
00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:07.600
Goodbye.
